{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:44:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:44:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"462"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/462"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.02,0.03,0.06,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95597"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/462"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"3855"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46372"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95597"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of cough, fatigue, and left shoulder pain. The cough is different from his usual smoker\u0027s cough. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and hypertension treated with perindopril for six months. He takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 86/min, blood pressure 144/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is reduced sweating on the left side of his face. His chest is barrel-shaped with dullness to percussion and reduced breath sounds at the left base. An urgent chest x-ray performed reveals a left apical mass.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is the most appropriate to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT chest","Sputum cytology","Pleural aspiration","PET/CT","CT-guided needle biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suspicious for lung cancer, specifically a superior sulcus (Pancoast) tumour. The combination of shoulder pain, Horner\u0027s syndrome (indicated by facial anhidrosis), and signs of pleural effusion in a heavy smoker strongly suggests malignancy. The chest x-ray finding of a left apical mass further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT-guided needle biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis as it provides tissue for histological confirmation of malignancy. Given the peripheral location of Pancoast tumours, it is often accessible by percutaneous needle biopsy. This is essential for determining the specific type of lung cancer and planning appropriate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest\u003C/strong\u003E is an important initial imaging investigation but cannot provide definitive tissue diagnosis. It would typically be performed first to guide the biopsy approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum cytology\u003C/strong\u003E has low sensitivity for diagnosing lung cancer, particularly for peripheral lesions like Pancoast tumours. While it is non-invasive, its diagnostic yield is insufficient for definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E may provide cytology if pleural fluid is present but is less reliable than direct tissue biopsy for confirming lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET/CT\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for staging once the diagnosis is confirmed but does not provide tissue diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Classic features of a Pancoast tumour include shoulder pain, Horner\u0027s syndrome and neurological changes in the upper limb.","Tissue diagnosis is essential for confirming the diagnosis of lung cancer.\n.","Given the peripheral location of Pancoast tumours, it is often accessible by percutaneous needle biopsy"],"references":["McLellan R, Marshall H, Dent A, Bowman R, Yang I, Fong K. Diagnosis and treatment of early lung cancer. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2020 Jul 31;49:508\u201312. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/august/diagnosis-and-treatment-of-early-lung-cancer","Cancer Australia, 2020. Evidence report for Investigating symptoms of lung cancer: a guide for all health professionals, Cancer Australia, Surry Hills, NSW. Available at: https://www.canceraustralia.gov.au/ISLCguide","Panagopoulos N, Leivaditis V, Koletsis E, et al. Pancoast tumors: characteristics and preoperative assessment. J Thorac Dis. 2014;6 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S108-S115. doi:10.3978/j.issn.2072-1439.2013.12.29. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24672686/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78408"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"462"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78408","links":{